	<h1>Programming Languages</h1><h2>Compiling Techniques</h2><h3>Conway's separable transition diagrams and coroutines</h3><a href="http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=366704&coll=portal&dl=ACM&CFID=7194043&CFTOKEN=34956787">ACM Portal Citation</a>.&nbsp; Conway, Melvin E.  Design of a separable transition-diagram compiler.  <i>Comm. ACM <b>6</b></i>, 7 (July 1963),  396-408.  <a href="http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/366663.366704">http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/366663.366704</a><br /><br />This paper provided a general approach to syntax-oriented parsing and also introduced coroutine coupling as a way to connect the stages of a compiler so that each appears to be the client of a service provided by the other.&nbsp; This is the standard solution, and not object-object message-passing as is supposed in high-level discussions of how compiler operations are coordinated between the abstraction levels: text, lexical, syntactic, semantic, code assembly, etc.<br>
